      "first_name": "William Henry",
      "last_name": "Foster",
      "born_year": 1865,
      "born_place": "Nottingham",
      "bio": "William Henry Foster (b. c. 1865, Nottingham) was a furniture manufacturer, the son of Mary and William Foster Jr, and grandson of William Foster who was an upholsterer, Alderman and Lord Mayor of Nottingham 1872\u201373, who established the family firm in 1845. William Henry lived at 6 Park Terrace with his wife Pearlie (from Wellington, New Zealand) and their daughters.\n\nWilliam Henry Foster's father, William Foster Jr. (c.1840\u2013c.1927), took over full control of Foster and Cooper following the dissolution of his partnership with John Cooper on 5th September 1887. William Foster Jr. built 27 Newcastle Drive and lived there from 1884 until after 1911. William Henry was living with his parents at \"Glendower\" in 1891.\n\nThe firm later became Foster, Cooper & Foster after William Henry joined. Activities described as \"Cabinet makers, upholsterers, carpet & floor cloth warehousemen, furnishing contractors, mattress, bed & bedding manufacturers, designers and makers of art cabinet furniture, and dealers in feathers, flocks, etc.\" (Kelly, 1891). From at least 1885 until 1927 the firm had premises at 63\u201364 Long Row and 73\u201379 Upper Parliament Street; workshops at 156\u2013158 Arkwright Street in the 1880s\u201390s; and from at least 1915\u201327 had works at Wilford Crescent East. William Henry remained as managing director until at least 1927.\n\nHis uncle, the lace manufacturer Thomas Parkin Foster, was also resident at Duke William Mount in The Park in 1901.",
